Using super.hashCode() for PartitionKeyInternal and VectorSessionToken

timeline.bodyText: Curious: I do not see that this override is required. I sometimes include overrides for debugging purposes. Is that what this one is for or am I missing something?
timeline.author: David-Noble-at-work

replies.bodyText:
It is flagged by the compiler indicating that while this type has a specialized implementation for equals() but hashCode is missing.
Reference: "if you are overriding equals method, you should override the hash code method too" -> https://java2blog.com/hashcode-and-equals-method-in-java/
replies.author: anuchandy

replies.bodyText:
I see that an issue has been logged to implement what I would expect to see: an implementation different than super.hashCode.
Question: Have we switched from TODO () to "Note: @" as a marker for work to be done?
replies.author: David-Noble-at-work

timeline.bodyText:
Some additional context on the changes to this file would be helpful. I see a switch with breaks added and a note to verify that the fall-through was unintentional. I know that checkstyle and stopbugs complain about fall-throughs within switches and also about braces around case statements.
Was the fall-through unintentional?
If that's the case is the note still needed?
To satisfy checkstyle should we not remove the braces around the case statements?
